# X-Ray Diffraction Crystal Classifier

I built this to classify X-ray diffraction patterns into crystal systems 
using a fine-tuned ResNet-18, trained on synthetic data generated from real 
Materials Project crystal structures. The project is meant to connect to 
the kind of work done at the ESRF synchrotron in Grenoble, where I study.

## Preview

![Upload and prediction](screenshot2.png)
![Probability chart and explanation](screenshot.png)


## What it does

- Generates synthetic XRD patterns from ~1,750 real crystal structures 
  pulled from the Materials Project database, using pymatgen's XRD 
  calculator
- Classifies an uploaded diffraction pattern into one of 7 crystal systems 
  (cubic, hexagonal, monoclinic, orthorhombic, tetragonal, trigonal, 
  triclinic)
- Shows the model's confidence and a probability breakdown across all 7 
  classes
- Calls Mistral AI to explain the prediction — what the crystal system 
  means, real examples, and why the diffraction pattern looks the way it 
  does


## Technologies used

| Category | Tools |
| Deep Learning | PyTorch, torchvision (ResNet-18, transfer learning) |
| Scientific Data | pymatgen, Materials Project API |
| Visualization | plotly |
| Web App | Streamlit |
| AI Explanation | Mistral AI API |
| Training | Google Colab (GPU) |
| Environment | python-dotenv |


## Data source

I pulled real crystal structures from the [Materials 
Project](https://materialsproject.org) database - 150,000+ computed 
structures, free to query through their API. For each one, pymatgen's 
`XRDCalculator` computes a theoretical diffraction pattern (Cu-Kα 
radiation). I render each pattern as a "reciprocal space pixel strip" — 
intensity mapped to pixel brightness across a 224-pixel strip, then tiled 
vertically into a 224×224 grayscale image. Each structure gets perturbed 
(±3% lattice scaling) and intensity-jittered 3 times, which gave me about 
5,250 training images.


## The Engineering Journey
## How I got here (the debugging part)

My first version plateaued at ~32% accuracy — barely better than guessing 
randomly across 7 classes. I tried more epochs, unfreezing more layers, 
adding data augmentation — nothing moved the needle. That was the signal 
that something was wrong with the data representation itself, not the 
training setup.

Turned out the problem was how I was drawing the patterns. Thin lines on 
a mostly-black image lose information when they pass through ResNet's 
pooling layers — small peaks were getting averaged away before the model 
ever saw them. I switched to encoding intensity as pixel brightness in a 
strip that spans the full image height, so peaks survive downsampling no 
matter what. I also swapped ResNet's first layer to take 1-channel 
grayscale input directly instead of faking RGB by tripling the same 
channel three times.

That fixed the underfitting — loss actually started dropping. But then I 
hit the opposite problem: training loss collapsed to near zero while test 
accuracy stayed flat. The model was just memorizing the exact pixel 
positions of my synthetic peaks, since pymatgen always outputs the same 
theoretical pattern for a given structure. I fixed this by randomly 
perturbing the crystal lattice by a few percent and jittering peak 
intensities before generating each image, plus dropout, label smoothing, 
and stronger weight decay on the model side.

## Where it landed

60% accuracy on the test set. Looking at the confusion matrix, the model 
is genuinely good at cubic (81% F1) and triclinic (68% F1) — the two 
extremes of crystal symmetry, which makes sense since they produce the 
most distinctive patterns. It struggles more with systems that are 
geometrically close to each other, like orthorhombic vs. monoclinic 
(39 misclassifications, the largest single confusion in the matrix) and 
hexagonal vs. trigonal. That's not just a model weakness — real 
crystallographers run into the same ambiguity and need more than peak 
position alone to tell these apart.

