## Future work
The most promising next step is probably a 1D CNN trained directly on the 
intensity arrays instead of rendering them as images first — that's 
closer to how the underlying physics actually works, and would skip the 
whole image-encoding problem entirely.


## How to run locally

**1. Clone the repository**
```bash
git clone https://github.com/anzhekalka/xray-crystal-classifier.git
cd xray-crystal-classifier
```

**2. Create a virtual environment**
```bash
python -m venv .venv
source .venv/bin/activate
```

**3. Install dependencies**
```bash
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

**4. Add your API keys**

Create a `.env` file in the root folder:
  MISTRAL_API_KEY=your_mistral_key_here
  MATERIALS_PROJECT_API_KEY=your_materials_project_key_here

Get a free Mistral key at [console.mistral.ai](https://console.mistral.ai)
Get a free Materials Project key at [materialsproject.org](https://materialsproject.org)

**5. Generate the dataset** *(optional — only needed to retrain)*
```bash
python data_download.py
```

**6. Train the model** *(optional — pretrained model included, GPU recommended)*
```bash
python train.py
```

**7. Run the app**
```bash
streamlit run app.py
```
Open your browser at `http://localhost:8501`


## Project structure 
```
xray-crystal-classifier/

├── data/                  ← synthetic XRD pattern images (not in repo)

├── model/                 ← trained model weights + class labels

├── data_download.py       ← downloads structures + generates patterns

├── dataset.py              ← PyTorch dataset/dataloader pipeline

├── train.py                ← trains and evaluates the CNN (run on GPU/Colab)

├── explainer.py            ← Mistral AI scientific explanation

├── app.py                  ← Streamlit web app

├── requirements.txt

└── .env                    ← API keys (never shared)
```

## What I learned

- How transfer learning and fine-tuning work in practice (freezing/
  unfreezing layers, modifying architecture for custom input channels)
- How to systematically diagnose underfitting vs. overfitting from loss 
  curves and confusion matrices
- Why data augmentation can hurt scientific data when it distorts 
  physically meaningful signal (e.g., rotation/flipping on diffraction 
  patterns)
- GPU training workflows (Google Colab, device management, syncing code 
  via GitHub and data via Google Drive)
- The physics of X-ray diffraction and crystal symmetry systems
- Real engineering judgment: knowing when a result is "good enough" given 
  the genuine difficulty of the problem
